"1205–1253":"1205–1253","1206–1244":"1206–1244","1210–Male":"1210–Overleden","1145–1193":"1145–1193","1144–1208":"1144–1208","before 1205":"vóór 1205","1253":"1253","1193":"1193","1180":"1180","1206":"1206","1205":"1205","1249":"1249","1227":"1227","1223":"1223","1179":"1179","Abt 1177":"circa 1177","1145":"1145","1244":"1244","1178":"1178","about 1205":"circa 1205","1144":"1144","1210":"1210","1177":"1177","about 1210":"circa 1210","1208":"1208","about 1175":"circa 1175","Durham, England":"Durham, England","England":"England","High Worsall Manor, Northallerton, Yorkshire North Riding, England":"Northallerton, Yorkshire, England"},"en":{"Abt 1177–":"about 1177–Deceased","1177–Female":"1177–Deceased","1178–1227":"1178–1227","1180–1249":"1180–1249","1179–1223":"1179–1223","1205–1253":"1205–1253","1206–1244":"1206–1244","1210–Male":"1210–Deceased","1145–1193":"1145–1193","1144–1208":"1144–1208","before 1205":"before 1205","1253":"1253","1193":"1193","1180":"1180","1206":"1206","1205":"1205","1249":"1249","1227":"1227","1223":"1223","1179":"1179","Abt 1177":"about 1177","1145":"1145","1244":"1244","1178":"1178","about 1205":"about 1205","1144":"1144","1210":"1210","1177":"1177","about 1210":"about 1210","1208":"1208","about 1175":"about 1175","Durham, England":"Durham, England","England":"England","High Worsall Manor, Northallerton, Yorkshire North Riding, England":"Northallerton, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Neville","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Irish (of Norman origin): habitational name from Neuville in Calvados or Néville in Seine-Maritime, both so called from Old French <i>neu(f)</i> ‘new’ (from Latin <i>novus</i>) + <i>ville</i> ‘settlement’. One family line, originally from Neuville (Calvados), became powerful during the Wars of the Roses through Richard <i>Neville</i> (1428–71), 16th Earl of Warwick, nicknamed \"The Kingmaker\".","Irish (Munster): assimilation of the Gaelic name <b>Ó Niadh</b> (see   Nee  ) and sometimes of <b>Ó Cnaimhín</b> (see   Nevin  ).","History: George Neville came to VA in or <i>c.</i> 1700 and settled on the headwaters of the Occoquan River, acquiring a large estate. His descendants, bearing the surnames Neville and Craig, were of considerable importance in Pittsburgh, PA, and Cincinnati, OH."],"variants":[{"name":"Nevells","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Neville  ."]},{"name":"Nevils","meanings":["English: variant of   Neville  ."]},{"name":"Novel","meanings":["English: variant of   Neville  .","Catalan: variant of   Novell  ."]},{"name":"Newell","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Neville  .","English: variant of   Noel  .","English: variant of   Newhall  ."]},{"name":"Nevills","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Neville  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Nevil","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Neville  ."]},{"name":"Newill","meanings":["English and Irish (or Norman origin): variant of   Neville  ."]},{"name":"Nevill","meanings":["English and Irish: of Norman origin, a variant of   Neville  ."]},{"name":"Nevels","meanings":["English and Scottish (Wigtownshire): of Norman origin, a variant of   Neville  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. This surname is now rare in Britain.","Dutch and North German: unexplained."]},{"name":"Nee","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Dermot, John Patrick.","Irish (Galway): shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Niadh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Nia</i>’ or <b>Mac Niadh</b> ‘son of <i>Nia</i>’. Compare   McNee  .   Needham   2 and   Neville   have also been adopted as Anglicized forms of this name.","North German: possibly a relationship name from Middle Low German <i>neve</i> ‘nephew, grand-child’."]}]},{"name":"Avicia","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","m